@startuml Veloce_Architecture_Flow

' Configuration and Style settings
skinparam style strictuml
skinparam SequenceMessageAlignment center
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam MaxMessageSize 400

' Define distinct, colored participants to differentiate layers
actor "User" as U #FFD700
box "Angular Frontend (Client)" #E3F2FD
participant "HomePage Component" as HPFE #7c7cbc
participant "Products Component" as PFE #7c7cbc
participant "Product Data Service" as SFE #7c7cbc
participant "errorHandler Helper" as EHR #7c7cbc
end box

box "Node.js Backend (API)" #E0F2F1
participant "Controller" as CTRL #008080
participant "Model" as M #20B2AA
end box

database "MySQL Database" as DB #FF8C00

' == 1. Application Initialization (Auto-Switched Banner) ==

note over  U 
Upon the user accessing the application, the system
automatically initializes the home component and begins
 the auto-switching banner process to showcase the
 different bike models. A `setInterval` is
 established to run every 4 seconds, directly modifying a
 Signal that the template is bound to, which ensures a smooth and  dynamic experience. 
end note

U -> HPFE : Access Veloce Application
activate HPFE
loop Every 4 Seconds (until navigation occurs)
   
   note over HPFE
   A timer fires, triggering the next step in the loop.
   The Angular component logic calculates the next index
   in the image array and updates the signal holding the
   current image URL. This reactive signal update
   immediately forces the DOM to re-render the banner with
   the new image.
   end note 

    HPFE -> HPFE : Update backgroundImageUrl Signal
    note over HPFE
    The DOM re-renders to display the new hero image to the user.
    end note

    HPFE --> U : Render New Hero Image
end

' == 2. Product Catalog Retrieval (Complete flow with error handling) ==

note over U
When the user scrolls into the 'Products' section or
clicks 'Products' in the main navigation, the main catalog
retrieval process begins. The Angular component listens
for this event and immediately delegates the data-fetching
responsibility to the dedicated Product Data Service.

end note 

U -> HPFE : Scroll to 'Products' or Click 'Products' in Navbar
activate PFE
HPFE -> PFE : Activate Component / Activate Route
PFE -> SFE : getAllProducts()
activate SFE

group try [Successful API Call]
    
    note over SFE

    The Data Service makes a specific `GET` request
    to the `/getAllProducts` API endpoint.

    end note

    SFE -> CTRL : HTTP GET /api/products/getAllProducts
    activate CTRL
    
    note over CTRL
    The Express Controller receives the catalog request
    and acts as the gatekeeper, delegating the data-level
    operations to the Node.js Model. The controller calls
    the `AllProducts()` method,
    end note 
    CTRL -> M : AllProducts()
    activate M
    
    note over M
    The Model utilizes the established database
    connection to execute a Query in the products table. 
    The Database engine processes this standard SQL command,
     scans the specified table, and retrieves all relevant product rows. 
     Once completed, the Databas sends the resulting dataset back to the Model as a structured array of objects.

    end note 

    M -> DB : invokes a Query to get some results
    activate DB
    DB --> M : Return Product Rows Array[]
    deactivate DB
    
    note Over M 
    The Model receives the raw rows and passes the entire
    array back to the Controller function that initiated
    the call.

    end note 

    M --> CTRL : Return Product Data Object
    deactivate M
    CTRL --> SFE : HTTP 200 (JSON Product List)
    
   note over SFE 
   The Data Service successfully receives the JSON payload.
    It then pushes this raw data back to the original Products Component. 
    The component then uses this data to update its own reactive product signal. 
    Since the HTML template is bound to this signal, Angular instantly iterates through the array, 
    rendering individual bike cards and presenting the complet Veloce catalog to the user.
   end note 
    SFE --> PFE : Return Data Object[]
    PFE -> PFE : Render Product Cards in DOM
    PFE --> U : Display Bike Catalog
    deactivate SFE
    
else catch [API or Server Error (e.g., DB Down)]
  note over DB
  The catch block activates immediately when an error
  occurs. If the database connection fails, the MySQL
  driver in the backend will throw an exception. The Model
  catches this error but, unable to resolve it, re-throws
  it to the Controller. The Controller catches this
  server-side error and responds to the frontend with an
  HTTP 500 (Internal Server Error) status, providing a
  generic error message for security.
  end note
    DB -[#red]> CTRL : Database Connection/Query Error
    CTRL -[#red]> SFE : HTTP 500 (Internal Server Error)
    deactivate CTRL
    
    note over SFE 
    The Angular Data Service detects the non-200 status
    code and converts the HTTP failure into an observable
    error. This service does not handle the error itself
    but instead passes (re-throws) the error object to the
    component that called it. The component receives the
    error and delegates the final handling to the
    specialized `errorHandler` helper function, which is
    centralized to manage all application alerts.
    end note 

    SFE -[#red]> PFE : Throw Service Error (Observable error)
    PFE -[#red]> EHR : Invoke errorHandler(error)
    activate EHR
    
    note over EHR 
     The centralized `errorHandler` helper receives the
     raw error object, logs the technical details for
     debugging, and translates it into a user-friendly
     message. It then triggers a "Toast" service to
     display a non-intrusive, timed alert notification at
     the top of the user's screen.
     end note
    EHR -> EHR : Trigger Toast Notification
    EHR -[#red]> U : Display Alert: "Failed to load products"
    deactivate EHR
end

deactivate PFE

' == 3. Product Quick View (Popup with specific data) ==

note over U
The user finds a bike they are interested in and clicks on
that specific product card. Angular's event system
captures this click, identifies which unique product ID
was clicked and triggers the `getAllProductDetails(id)`method in the Products Component. 
This method immediately initiates the process to display
the detailed Quick View popup.
end note 

U -> PFE : Click on a Product Card
activate PFE
note over PFE
The component logic identifies the product ID and calls
the Data Service, passing that ID as a crucial parameter.
end note 

PFE -> SFE : getAllProductDetails(productId)
activate SFE

group try [Successful Quick View Retrieval]
    note over SFE
    The Data Service makes a specific `GET` request.
    Crucially, as we established in our path-matching
    correction earlier, the product ID is appended to the
    URL as a path parameter. This ensures the request is REST-compliant. 
    The Router receives this specific path request and 
    routes it directly to the Controller's specialized function,
     preparing it to process that unique ID

    end note 


    SFE -> CTRL : HTTP GET /api/products/getAllProductDetails/1
    activate CTRL
    note over CTRL
    The Controller receives the request and
    immediately extracts the ID from the `req.params
    productId`. Since the ID comes as a string, the
    controller converts it to a Number and stores it.

    end note
    CTRL -> CTRL : Extract & Convert 'req.params.productId' to Number
    
  note over CTRL
  The Controller then delegates the data request to the
  specialized Model function. It calls `getProductById()`,
  passing the clean, numeric ID. The Model utilizes its
  knowledge of the schema structure to execute that
  crucial SQL query using `LEFT JOIN`s against both the
  `productSpecifications` and `productsImages` tables,
  which efficiently aggregates all specifications and
  gallery images into a single result.
  end note 
    CTRL -> M : getProductById(1)
    activate M
    M -> DB : SELECT with LEFT JOIN (Specs + 4 Images)
    activate DB
    DB --> M : Return Unified Row Data
    deactivate DB

    note over M 
    The Model processes the joined result set. If the bike
    has multiple images, it collapses these into a proper
    JSON structure, ensuring the frontend receives a clean
    object with a gallery array. This formatted object is
    then passed back to the Controller. The Express
    Controller completes the round-trip by sending this
    product detail object back to the Angular client with an HTTP 200 (OK) status code

    end note 

    M --> CTRL : Return Product Detail Object
    deactivate M
    CTRL --> SFE : HTTP 200 (JSON Product Object)
    
   note over SFE
   The Data Service receives the JSON and pushes the
   product object back to the Products Component. Having
   successfully retrieved the data, the component
   activates the Quick View Modal/Popup.
   end note

    SFE --> PFE : Return Product Detail Object
    PFE -> PFE : Open Popup, Set signals, and Lock Body Scroll
    PFE --> U : Display "Quick View" Popup
    deactivate SFE
    
else catch [Detail Fetch Error]
   
   note over SFE 
   If a network error occurs during the GET call, the
   service intercepts the fault, converts it to an
   observable error, and re-throws it. The component
   catches this error and invokes the centralized
   `errorHandler` helper. The  helper then triggers a
   specific toast alert to inform the user of the problem
   end note

    SFE -[#red]> PFE : Throw Error to Component
    PFE -[#red]> EHR : Invoke errorHandler(error)
    activate EHR
    EHR -> EHR : Trigger Toast Notification
    EHR -[#red]> U : Display Alert: "Error fetching details"
    deactivate EHR
    deactivate CTRL
end
deactivate PFE

@enduml